<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-388-002  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 388 002.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DEC User  June 1989 p51(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM jumps on the single architecture bandwagon.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Butler, Martin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM has developed the Systems Applications Architecture (SAA) inresponse to DEC's single-architecture product line to cope withthe multiplicity of hardware platforms the company has inherited.andO;SAA is a high-level architecture, while DEC's VAX-VMS operates ata lower level.andP;  It addresses several software areas across IBM'splatforms: the Common Programming Interface, which definesstandards for programming languages; Common CommunicationsSupport, designed to connect applications over OS-2, OS-400 andMVS platforms; and Common User Access, a standard user interfacewhich will result in applications presenting the same features tousers on different platforms.andP;  DEC is not likely to need its ownversion of SAA because it is rapidly moving to open industry-widesystems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     System DesignSAAApplicationsUser InterfaceSoftware ArchitectureOperating Environments.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   These hardware platforms and operating systems are covered by SAA.andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>